ctions beyond surface-level definitions.","why_cuet_level":"Requires analysis of statements rather than mere recall of definitions.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correct, it highlights the importance of chelation in coordination chemistry.","B":"Partially correct but overlooks the uniqueness of chelating ligands' role.","C":"Incorrect; both statements have validity in context with Statement I being accurate.","D":"Misleading because it dismisses the established role of chelating ligands."}},{"q":"When comparing octahedral complexes, a student claims that all will exhibit identical magnetic properties due to their geometry. Which response best corrects this misunderstanding?","o":["Geometry influences but does not solely determine magnetic properties; electronic configuration plays a key role.","All octahedral complexes must be paramagnetic due to unpaired electrons in their d-orbitals.","Magnetic properties are fixed for octahedral complexes regardless of ligand type or metal center.","All octahedral complexes are diamagnetic if they have no unpaired electrons."],"a":"A","question_type":"comparison_based","concept_id":"chemistry::coordination_compounds","trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"This question targets misconceptions about geometry and its implications on magnetic properties in coordination compounds.","why_cuet_level":"Encourages deeper analysis of factors affecting magnetic behavior beyond simple geometry.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correct; it acknowledges that geometry is just one factor influencing magnetism.","B":"Incorrect; while some octahedral may be paramagnetic, this isn't universal for all.","C":"Misleading since magnetic properties vary significantly based on specific conditions and configurations.","D":"Incorrect; diamagnetism depends entirely on electron pairing which varies among complexes."}},{"q":"A learner suggests that all bidentate ligands create stronger complexes than monodentate ligands due to more 