ncept_id":"chemistry::isolation_of_elements","trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The question evaluates understanding of extraction efficiency rather than definitions.","why_cuet_level":"Students must discern between method effectiveness and theoretical outcomes, promoting deeper comprehension.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correctly identifies the limitations of Statement II regarding extraction efficiency.","B":"Incorrectly asserts that electrolytic methods are completely ineffective for reactive metals.","C":"Misrepresents electrolytic reduction as universally unsuitable for any reactivity level.","D":"Fails to recognize that while Statement I is true, Statement II is an overgeneralization."}},{"q":"In a discussion about methods of extracting metals, a student claims that hydrometallurgy is only useful for low-reactivity metals. Which response best challenges this view?","o":["Hydrometallurgy can also be effectively applied to some high-reactivity metals under specific conditions.","Hydrometallurgy exclusively targets low-reactivity metals due to safety concerns with high-reactive ones.","This method is limited to only non-metallic elements and does not apply to any metals at all.","Hydrometallurgy relies solely on temperature and pressure, making it unsuitable for most metals."],"a":"A","question_type":"case_based","concept_id":"chemistry::isolation_of_elements","trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The case encourages evaluation of hydrometallurgical applications beyond mere definitions or examples.","why_cuet_level":"Students must analyze specific conditions under which hydrometallurgy can be applied, promoting critical thinking.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correctly points out that hydrometallurgy has broader applications than suggested by the student.","B":"Misunderstands hydrometallurgy's scope by limiting it strictly to low-reactivity contexts.","C":"Incorrectly states that hydrometallurgy cannot apply to any metallic elements at all.","D":"Overemphasizes temperature and pressure as sole factors, ignoring other variables."}},{"q":"When comparing pyrometallurgy and hydrometallurgy, a learner states that both processes are equally effective for all types of ores. What correction best addresses this misconception?","o":["Pyrometallurgy is generally more suitable for sulfide ores while hydrometallurgy works better with oxide ores under certain conditions.","Both processes can be used interchangeably regardless of ore type due to their similar mechanisms of action.","Hydrometallurgy is always more effective since it avoids the high temperatures needed in pyrometallurgy entirely.","Pyrometallurgy should be used exclusively as it guarantees higher yields across all ore types."],"a":"A","question_type":"comparison_based","concept_id":"chemistry::isolation_of_elements","trap_option":"B","strong_distractors":["C","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The question promotes understanding of comparative advantages rather than simple definitions or applications.","why_cuet_level":"Students must evaluate different metallurgical methods in context rather than relying on surface-level comparisons.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"Correctly distinguishes between the specific suitability of each method based on ore composition.","B":"Incorrectly suggests that both methods can be used without consideration of ore characteristics.","C":"Misleads by implying hydrometallurgy's superiority without acknowledging its limitations in certain contexts.","D":"Oversimplifies pyrometallurgy's effectiveness by ignoring variations in yield based on ore type."}},{"q":"A learner argues that concentration processes are unnecessary if reduction follows directly after ore extraction. Which statement provides the best counter-argument?","o":["Concentration enhances metal recovery rates by reducing waste material before reduction takes place.","Reduction alone suffices because it converts ores directly into 